thread.title: Economy added 142,000 jobs in September, lower than expected
thread.title_full: Economy added 142,000 jobs in September, lower than expected - POLITICO

author: Timothy Noah
title: Economy added 142,000 jobs in September, lower than expected
text:
The economy added 142,000 jobs in September, the Labor Department reported Friday in a jobs report that may give the Federal Reserve second thoughts about raising interest rates. The previous estimate for August's jobs increase was adjusted downward from 173,000 to 136,000. That was a surprise, as the Labor Department's first estimate for August employment is typically adjusted upward.
Unemployment was 5.1 percent, unchanged from August, and average hourly private-sector earnings were down a penny. In August they were up 8 cents.
The slippage makes it less likely that the Federal Reserve Board will raise interest rates later this month, or possibly even in December. Fed Chair Janet Yellen has said she expects an interest-rate hike by year's end, and most analysts expected that to occur when the Fed's Open Markets Committee met Dec. 15-16.
But Jeffrey Lacker, chairman of the Richmond Fed, told The Wall Street Journal Thursday that a hike might come earlier, when the committee meets Oct. 27-28. Such an outcome is more difficult to imagine now.
Analysts had predicted the creation of about 203,000 jobs, an unemployment rate of 5.1 percent and an increase in hourly earnings of 0.2 percent, according to a Bloomberg survey of economists . The payroll company ADP estimated Wednesday, based on its own records, that September job growth in the private sector was 200,000, up from its August calculation of 190,000.
The jobs report followed news last week from the Commerce Department that GDP increased 3.9 percent during the second quarter of 2015, a small improvement over its previous second-quarter estimate of 3.7 percent and a large one over the first quarterâ€™s 0.6 percent growth.
But other economic news has been less favorable. Analysts expect a slowdown in the third quarter, with the Atlanta Fed forecasting a GDP growth rate of 0.9 percent. The Commerce Department's first cut at estimating third quarter growth will be released Oct. 29.
Another unfavorable sign of the economy's course: Labor force participation dropped further to 62.4 percent, down from the 62.6 percent.rate that prevailed in June, July and August, which was already its lowest level since the 1970s.
